Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.830 --> 00:00:05.000
Prof: Let's start.
 

00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:09.292
I told you about Ampere's law,
which is key to what we are

00:00:09.292 --> 00:00:12.606
going to do next,
so I'll remind you what the

00:00:12.606 --> 00:00:13.510
deal is.
 

00:00:13.510 --> 00:00:22.043
It says, if you have a closed
loop and around that loop you

00:00:22.043 --> 00:00:28.517
integrate the magnetic field
that is equal to

00:00:28.517 --> 00:00:37.051
Î¼_0 times all the
currents that penetrate this

00:00:37.051 --> 00:00:38.670
loop.
 

00:00:38.670 --> 00:00:43.912
So some current would be going
in, some current would be coming

00:00:43.912 --> 00:00:44.420
out.
 

00:00:44.420 --> 00:00:46.840
The guys who are outside the
loop don't contribute.

00:00:46.840 --> 00:00:50.960
Guys who are trapped inside
this, they make a contribution.

00:00:50.960 --> 00:00:58.210
That's Ampere's law.
 

00:00:58.210 --> 00:01:00.140
Now you have to know the
convention.

00:01:00.140 --> 00:01:04.872
The convention is that you do
the line integral

00:01:04.872 --> 00:01:07.980
counterclockwise,
and if your fingers are

00:01:07.980 --> 00:01:11.204
following the line integral,
your thumb points towards

00:01:11.204 --> 00:01:14.968
outside the board,
and that current is positive.

00:01:14.968 --> 00:01:17.805
Anything going into the board
therefore will be counted as

00:01:17.805 --> 00:01:18.950
negative in this one.
 

00:01:18.950 --> 00:01:22.519
So this has to be counted with
sign, do you understand?

00:01:22.519 --> 00:01:25.983
If the contour goes one way,
all currents coming out of the

00:01:25.983 --> 00:01:28.433
board are positive,
all those going in are

00:01:28.433 --> 00:01:29.209
negative.
 

00:01:29.209 --> 00:01:32.305
In particular,
if these 4 currents add up

00:01:32.305 --> 00:01:35.007
algebraically to 0,
one is 2 amp,

00:01:35.007 --> 00:01:38.928
another is -2 amp and so on,
then this integral will vanish,

00:01:38.928 --> 00:01:40.599
even though there are currents.
 

00:01:40.599 --> 00:01:44.654
So it counts not the absolute
value but the algebraic sum of

00:01:44.654 --> 00:01:45.959
all the currents.
 

00:01:45.959 --> 00:01:49.019
Now there's another subtlety I
didn't get into last time,

00:01:49.019 --> 00:01:56.616
which is the following -
remember, this is the current

00:01:56.616 --> 00:02:02.849
penetrating a surface,
bounded by this loop.

00:02:02.849 --> 00:02:05.519
You guys with me on what that
means?

00:02:05.519 --> 00:02:09.324
Now as long as I force you to
put this loop and to live in the

00:02:09.324 --> 00:02:12.628
plane of the blackboard,
there's only one surface with

00:02:12.628 --> 00:02:14.500
that loop as the boundary.
 

00:02:14.500 --> 00:02:17.254
But in real life,
we are doing stuff in three

00:02:17.254 --> 00:02:18.068
dimensions.
 

00:02:18.068 --> 00:02:20.139
Imagine pulling this loop out
of the blackboard.

00:02:20.139 --> 00:02:22.389
A lot of currents are coming
and going out.

00:02:22.389 --> 00:02:27.729
What is the surface of which
this loop is the boundary?

00:02:27.729 --> 00:02:30.449
The answer is not unique.
 

00:02:30.449 --> 00:02:33.406
There are many,
many surfaces that have the

00:02:33.406 --> 00:02:35.870
same loop as the boundary,
right?

00:02:35.870 --> 00:02:40.000
Take a piece of wire and wrap
it in the form of this boundary

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:42.685
and dip it in soap,
and you pull it out,

00:02:42.685 --> 00:02:44.818
you'll get a soap filament.
 

00:02:44.818 --> 00:02:48.818
That soap filament has as its
rim, or the boundary,

00:02:48.818 --> 00:02:49.780
this loop.
 

00:02:49.780 --> 00:02:52.150
That may not even be planar.
 

00:02:52.150 --> 00:02:54.390
And if you blow on it,
it's going to bulge outside,

00:02:54.390 --> 00:02:54.750
right?
 

00:02:54.750 --> 00:02:58.074
Still this rim will be the
boundary of that bulging

00:02:58.074 --> 00:02:58.740
surface.
 

00:02:58.740 --> 00:03:02.275
So actually,
even if the surface is coming

00:03:02.275 --> 00:03:06.758
out of the blackboard,
the theorem is still valid.

00:03:06.758 --> 00:03:09.038
So let me draw another picture
that may be helpful.

00:03:09.038 --> 00:03:12.756
Suppose this is the surface and
you've got all these currents,

00:03:12.756 --> 00:03:14.949
some going in and some coming
out.

00:03:14.949 --> 00:03:18.038
You may have imagined all this
time I meant a flat planar

00:03:18.038 --> 00:03:18.590
surface.
 

00:03:18.590 --> 00:03:19.590
I don't.
 

00:03:19.590 --> 00:03:23.651
You can imagine now a curvy
surface, like maybe a

00:03:23.651 --> 00:03:28.220
hemisphere, of which this rim is
still the boundary.

00:03:28.220 --> 00:03:30.408
You can ask,
"How can that be?

00:03:30.408 --> 00:03:31.811
Where do you want me to count
the currents,

00:03:31.811 --> 00:03:32.878
here or on that surface?"
 

00:03:32.878 --> 00:03:36.410
The answer is,
it doesn't matter.

00:03:36.410 --> 00:03:41.800
It doesn't matter because any
current coming in here has to

00:03:41.800 --> 00:03:45.240
get out also through the other
one.

00:03:45.240 --> 00:03:48.098
The only--or it may come in and
decide to come back here,

00:03:48.098 --> 00:03:49.930
in which case it doesn't leave
the other one,

00:03:49.930 --> 00:03:53.494
but it will make 0 contribution
to this contour because it's

00:03:53.494 --> 00:03:55.669
coming in once and going out
once.

00:03:55.669 --> 00:03:58.733
Because currents don't
terminate, just like magnetic

00:03:58.733 --> 00:04:02.396
field lines, whatever crosses
this surface will also cross any

00:04:02.396 --> 00:04:04.500
surface with the same boundary.
 

00:04:04.500 --> 00:04:09.659
That's a fact that will become
important later on.

00:04:09.659 --> 00:04:10.639
So you follow that?
 

00:04:10.639 --> 00:04:14.360
The law, if you want to write
it formally,

00:04:14.360 --> 00:04:17.680
I'm going to write it as some
surface,

00:04:17.680 --> 00:04:20.389
and this is the surface
integral of the current density,

00:04:20.389 --> 00:04:22.290
which is the current per unit
area.

00:04:22.290 --> 00:04:25.454
And this loop is the boundary
of that surface,

00:04:25.454 --> 00:04:28.899
and I told you that the
boundary of any surface is

00:04:28.899 --> 00:04:31.149
written as partial S.
 

00:04:31.149 --> 00:04:34.170
This is the correct way to
write Ampere's law.

00:04:34.170 --> 00:04:39.547
And the point I'm making is,
this could be any surface with

00:04:39.547 --> 00:04:41.680
that as the boundary.
 

00:04:41.680 --> 00:04:45.795
Now once you've got Ampere's
law, I was trying to show you

00:04:45.795 --> 00:04:50.055
how you can use it to solve
certain problems that might have

00:04:50.055 --> 00:04:52.149
otherwise been difficult.
 

00:04:52.149 --> 00:04:53.750
Just like Gauss's law.
 

00:04:53.750 --> 00:04:57.095
Remember, Gauss's law was very
helpful when you took a solid

00:04:57.095 --> 00:04:58.060
ball of charge.
 

00:04:58.060 --> 00:05:00.538
The electric field of that is
usually hard to find,

00:05:00.538 --> 00:05:03.415
but from spherical symmetry,
you know the field is radially

00:05:03.415 --> 00:05:04.060
outwards.
 

00:05:04.060 --> 00:05:07.838
You draw a Gaussian surface and
you know the field's magnitude

00:05:07.838 --> 00:05:09.449
is constant on a sphere.
 

00:05:09.449 --> 00:05:10.170
How big is it?
 

00:05:10.170 --> 00:05:11.980
You get that from Gauss's law.
 

00:05:11.980 --> 00:05:15.560
So certain problems which are
highly symmetric,

00:05:15.560 --> 00:05:18.519
you can get using Ampere's law
also.

00:05:18.519 --> 00:05:20.776
So one example I did,
I want to repeat it,

00:05:20.776 --> 00:05:22.980
because one thing I said wasn't
right.

00:05:22.980 --> 00:05:27.071
There's this current going from
- to infinity,

00:05:27.071 --> 00:05:30.889
and we want to find the field
around it.

00:05:30.889 --> 00:05:33.269
If you do an honest
calculation, you will say,

00:05:33.269 --> 00:05:36.389
let me take a segment,
let me take a point,

00:05:36.389 --> 00:05:40.221
let me join the segment to that
point and take the cross product

00:05:40.221 --> 00:05:42.560
of the
dl with the R,

00:05:42.560 --> 00:05:42.879
etc.
 

00:05:42.879 --> 00:05:45.430
and so on, right?
 

00:05:45.430 --> 00:05:48.497
And it will give you a
contribution coming out of the

00:05:48.497 --> 00:05:51.329
blackboard, but then you have to
integrate it.

00:05:51.329 --> 00:05:54.680
Now you don't have to do all
that if you use symmetry.

00:05:54.680 --> 00:05:58.285
The symmetry argument would
tell you first of all that any

00:05:58.285 --> 00:06:01.954
field configuration you have
will be the same if you rotate

00:06:01.954 --> 00:06:03.410
it around a circle.
 

00:06:03.410 --> 00:06:06.680
Because if you look at the wire
end on and you turn the wire,

00:06:06.680 --> 00:06:09.899
it looks the same so the field
configuration should look the

00:06:09.899 --> 00:06:10.389
same.
 

00:06:10.389 --> 00:06:12.670
And I said there are only a
couple of things that have the

00:06:12.670 --> 00:06:13.110
property.
 

00:06:13.110 --> 00:06:14.959
Here's a good one.
 

00:06:14.959 --> 00:06:16.910
Maybe it does that.
 

00:06:16.910 --> 00:06:20.730
And the other one is this.
 

00:06:20.730 --> 00:06:21.980
Here is the wire.
 

00:06:21.980 --> 00:06:24.761
Notice if you turn the wire,
the wire looks the same,

00:06:24.761 --> 00:06:26.420
configuration looks the same.
 

00:06:26.420 --> 00:06:29.108
If you turn this wire around
its own axis,

00:06:29.108 --> 00:06:32.980
wire looks the same and the
configuration looks the same.

00:06:32.980 --> 00:06:37.713
Then I said we rule this guy
out, because magnetic field

00:06:37.713 --> 00:06:41.069
lines cannot come and end at a
point.

00:06:41.069 --> 00:06:43.187
Then I gave another
explanation, which is that if

00:06:43.187 --> 00:06:45.964
you reverse the current,
the field lines are supposed to

00:06:45.964 --> 00:06:47.733
go outwards,
but instead of reversing the

00:06:47.733 --> 00:06:49.857
current,
if I grab it and turn it by 180

00:06:49.857 --> 00:06:52.877
degrees around this axis,
then the lines will still go in

00:06:52.877 --> 00:06:54.569
but the current would be
reversed.

00:06:54.569 --> 00:06:59.319
So for whatever reason,
this is out and this is in.

00:06:59.319 --> 00:07:02.310
Then as to the direction of the
field,

00:07:02.310 --> 00:07:05.850
we also know that it has to be
perpendicular to the blackboard,

00:07:05.850 --> 00:07:09.156
because the two vectors whose
cross product determines it lie

00:07:09.156 --> 00:07:13.350
in the plane of the blackboard,
so the field has to come out.

00:07:13.350 --> 00:07:15.875
It has to come out and the
amount by which it comes out

00:07:15.875 --> 00:07:17.839
cannot change as you go around
the loop.

00:07:17.839 --> 00:07:23.521
And the answer can only depend
on how far you are from the

00:07:23.521 --> 00:07:24.220
wire.
 

00:07:24.220 --> 00:07:29.870
Then I write Ampere's law as
2Î R times B at

00:07:29.870 --> 00:07:34.370
the radius r =
Î¼_0 times the

00:07:34.370 --> 00:07:35.519
current.
 

00:07:35.519 --> 00:07:38.411
In other words,
I look at the wire from the

00:07:38.411 --> 00:07:42.269
end, and I take any contour I
like of radius r.

00:07:42.269 --> 00:07:45.220
Then since B is
tangential to the circle,

00:07:45.220 --> 00:07:47.829
the line integral is simply
2Î r times B,

00:07:47.829 --> 00:07:50.910
and that's the current
enclosed, so you find B.

00:07:50.910 --> 00:07:52.576
If you like,
B_

