00:08:08.673 --> 00:08:10.579
get it from Ampere's law.
 

00:08:10.579 --> 00:08:12.120
Then I did another variation.
 

00:08:12.120 --> 00:08:15.327
I definitely don't want to
repeat that, which is,

00:08:15.327 --> 00:08:17.199
what if the wire is thick.
 

00:08:17.199 --> 00:08:21.857
Not a point wire but got finite
thickness with current coming

00:08:21.857 --> 00:08:23.720
out of the blackboard.
 

00:08:23.720 --> 00:08:25.829
What is going to be the
magnetic field?

00:08:25.829 --> 00:08:30.408
Then the answer depends on
whether you pick a contour like

00:08:30.408 --> 00:08:33.298
this or a contour inside the
wire.

00:08:33.298 --> 00:08:38.119
And if you do the two things,
you'll find the field actually

00:08:38.119 --> 00:08:42.448
grows linearly inside,
then falls like 1 over r

00:08:42.448 --> 00:08:43.428
outside.
 

00:08:43.428 --> 00:08:46.830
Anyway, this is stuff I did
near the end.

00:08:46.830 --> 00:08:54.604
But now I want to consider two
new problems which I didn't

00:08:54.604 --> 00:08:57.058
study last time.
 

00:08:57.058 --> 00:09:01.760
The first one is going to be
very important,

00:09:01.760 --> 00:09:03.730
is the solenoid.
 

00:09:03.730 --> 00:09:06.869
If you imagine on a tube you
wrap some wire,

00:09:06.869 --> 00:09:10.740
and the wire is wrapped like
this many, many times.

00:09:10.740 --> 00:09:13.980
And you want to find the
magnetic field.

00:09:13.980 --> 00:09:19.350
Now one loop we know produces a
field that goes like this.

00:09:19.350 --> 00:09:24.686
You stack them up,
you expect the field to go like

00:09:24.686 --> 00:09:30.023
that inside the coil,
then sort of loop around and

00:09:30.023 --> 00:09:33.399
come back outside the coil.
 

00:09:33.399 --> 00:09:38.225
What we want to find out is the
strength of the field inside the

00:09:38.225 --> 00:09:40.139
coil, and also outside.
 

00:09:40.139 --> 00:09:45.469
So the way you handle this
problem, you've got to take an

00:09:45.469 --> 00:09:48.990
Amperian loop that looks like
this.

00:09:48.990 --> 00:09:53.427
If this is the cardboard on
which you wound that thing,

00:09:53.427 --> 00:09:58.440
see what this wire looks like
when you slice it vertically.

00:09:58.440 --> 00:10:00.048
That's the tube on which you
wrapped it.

00:10:00.048 --> 00:10:01.990
I want you to slice it
vertically.

00:10:01.990 --> 00:10:06.220
On the left hand side,
I've current coming in.

00:10:06.220 --> 00:10:11.288
On the right hand side--coming
out of the board and right,

00:10:11.288 --> 00:10:14.399
it's going on,
you guys see that?

00:10:14.399 --> 00:10:17.389
Wrap it around the solenoid and
slice it down the middle,

00:10:17.389 --> 00:10:19.633
then on this end,
the current's coming out,

00:10:19.633 --> 00:10:21.769
on this end,
the current's going in.

00:10:21.769 --> 00:10:23.970
So I'm showing you the cross
section of the tube.

00:10:23.970 --> 00:10:29.330
It looks like this.
 

00:10:29.330 --> 00:10:35.090
So first thing I want to argue
is that the field outside does

00:10:35.090 --> 00:10:40.082
not vary with distance,
because if I took a loop like

00:10:40.082 --> 00:10:45.220
this--it's not a real loop;
it's a mathematical loop on

00:10:45.220 --> 00:10:48.178
which I'm going to use Ampere's
law.

00:10:48.178 --> 00:10:51.442
I know the field outside is
going to be coming down,

00:10:51.442 --> 00:10:55.216
but maybe it's weaker here and
stronger here and that's what

00:10:55.216 --> 00:10:56.879
I'm going to rule out.
 

00:10:56.879 --> 00:11:00.139
You know how we can rule that
out?

00:11:00.139 --> 00:11:06.710
What would go wrong if the
field was weaker here than here?

00:11:06.710 --> 00:11:15.740
Something to do with Ampere's
law.

00:11:15.740 --> 00:11:17.659
Well, let me explain.
 

00:11:17.659 --> 00:11:21.100
Suppose you go around this loop.
 

00:11:21.100 --> 00:11:24.695
Here B and dl are
perpendicular,

00:11:24.695 --> 00:11:29.169
so there's no contribution to
Bâdl.

00:11:29.169 --> 00:11:31.509
Likewise here.
 

00:11:31.509 --> 00:11:35.883
Here you have a B going
one way and you have the same

00:11:35.883 --> 00:11:39.590
B but the path is going
the opposite way.

00:11:39.590 --> 00:11:43.048
Now these two have to cancel.
 

00:11:43.048 --> 00:11:46.931
These two have to cancel
because there is no current

00:11:46.931 --> 00:11:48.529
coming out of this.
 

00:11:48.529 --> 00:11:49.808
Because there's no current
coming out,

00:11:49.808 --> 00:11:52.200
this line integral has
vanished, therefore B

00:11:52.200 --> 00:11:54.926
times that length and B
times that length going the

00:11:54.926 --> 00:11:57.029
opposite way must be equal in
magnitude.

00:11:57.029 --> 00:12:01.256
That means the B here
must be as strong as the

00:12:01.256 --> 00:12:02.639
B there.
 

00:12:02.639 --> 00:12:06.370
So B doesn't vary when
you leave the wire.

00:12:06.370 --> 00:12:10.058
Well, I can keep on repeating
this argument until I go all the

00:12:10.058 --> 00:12:12.720
way to infinity,
but I know B is 0.

00:12:12.720 --> 00:12:17.120
Therefore coming from infinity
inwards, B is going to be

00:12:17.120 --> 00:12:18.538
0 everywhere here.
 

00:12:18.538 --> 00:12:21.158
That's only true for an
infinite solenoid.

00:12:21.158 --> 00:12:25.458
If you take a finite solenoid,
there will be lines coming in

00:12:25.458 --> 00:12:25.970
here.
 

00:12:25.970 --> 00:12:28.956
For an infinite solenoid,
is when the lines always go

00:12:28.956 --> 00:12:29.990
perpendicularly.
 

00:12:29.990 --> 00:12:33.710
See, in a finite solenoid,
you sort of know the lines will

00:12:33.710 --> 00:12:34.820
do this, right?
 

00:12:34.820 --> 00:12:37.557
They'll be perpendicular here,
but they could be at an angle

00:12:37.557 --> 00:12:37.928
there.
 

00:12:37.928 --> 00:12:41.743
But for an infinite solenoid,
every portion looks like you

00:12:41.743 --> 00:12:42.480
are here.
 

00:12:42.480 --> 00:12:45.360
The lines are only vertical,
they have no choice but to

00:12:45.360 --> 00:12:45.840
vanish.
 

00:12:45.840 --> 00:12:50.931
So the flux actually goes out
and returns on a sphere of

00:12:50.931 --> 00:12:51.950
infinity.
 

00:12:51.950 --> 00:12:56.178
So we only have to find the
magnetic field inside.

00:12:56.178 --> 00:13:00.389
So then you've got to do the
right hand rule and the right

00:13:00.389 --> 00:13:04.600
hand rule tells you the magnetic
field looks like that.

00:13:04.600 --> 00:13:09.590
And the question is,
how big is it?

00:13:09.590 --> 00:13:14.371
Once again, I want to argue
that the magnetic field is

00:13:14.371 --> 00:13:17.168
constant inside the solenoid.
 

00:13:17.168 --> 00:13:20.927
Now atleast now you should be
able to guess what argument I

00:13:20.927 --> 00:13:21.639
will use.
 

00:13:21.639 --> 00:13:27.654
The argument will be,
take an Amperian loop like this

00:13:27.654 --> 00:13:28.350
one.
 

00:13:28.350 --> 00:13:29.740
The two sides,
this and that,

00:13:29.740 --> 00:13:32.918
do not contribute because they
are perpendicular to the field.

00:13:32.918 --> 00:13:37.048
These two better make
cancelling contributions.

00:13:37.048 --> 00:13:38.980
And that's going up and that's
going down.

00:13:38.980 --> 00:13:41.346
For them to cancel,
the strength of the field here

00:13:41.346 --> 00:13:43.279
must be the same as the strength
